    "Management": {
      "text": "",
      "subsections": {
        "American_College_of_Chest_Physicians_2006_Guidelines": {
          "text": "Routine treatment with antibiotics is NOT necessary\nAntitussive agents can be useful (\ncodeine\n,\ndextromethorphan\n)\nIn individuals without comorbidities, antibiotics have NO IMPROVEMENT in symptoms or duration\n[2]\nDo not treat patients with antibiotics unless:\n[3]\nolder than 65 years\nRecent hospitalizations in the past year\nDiabetes\nOn chronic steroids\nIf treating based upon the above criteria then a 5 day treatment is preferred\n[4]\nBronchodilators only useful if there is wheezing\nDespite the recommendations for no antibiotics in the non complicated course of acute bronchitis, patients continue to receive antibiotic prescriptions\n[5]\nOral Steroids do not reduce duration or severity of symptoms in patients with acute bronchitis\n[6]",
          "tables": []
        }
      },
